<BaseLayout
  title="Why Your Restaurant's TikTok Isn't Growing (And How to Fix It) | TRG"
  description="Most restaurants post on TikTok and get nothing. The restaurants that go viral do one thing differently — and it's not what you think. A strategy guide for Toronto restaurant owners."
>
  <Navbar />

  <main>

    <!-- HERO -->
    <section style="background: #1A1A1A; color: #fff; padding: 100px 24px 80px; text-align: center;">
      <div style="display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
        <span style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: #E85D04; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Social Media</span>
        <span style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em;">9 min read</span>
        <span style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em;">March 2026</span>
      </div>
      <h1 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(28px, 4.5vw, 52px); line-height: 1.15; max-width: 780px; margin: 0 auto 24px; font-weight: 400;">
        Why Your Restaurant's TikTok Isn't Growing (And How to Fix It)
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size: 18px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.72); max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.7;">
        Most restaurants post on TikTok and get nothing. The restaurants that go viral do one thing differently — and it's not what you think.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
    <div style="background: #fff; color: #1A1A1A;">
      <div style="max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 64px 24px 80px;">

        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          We've built TikTok accounts for Toronto restaurants that reached 113K followers and 500 million combined impressions. We've also seen hundreds of restaurant accounts post consistently for months and get nothing — 200 views per video, zero new customers, complete frustration. The difference between those two outcomes isn't luck. It's not budget. It's a fundamental misunderstanding of what TikTok's algorithm rewards and how food content actually spreads on the platform.
        </p>

        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Here's what the restaurants with dead TikTok accounts are doing wrong — and the specific changes that actually work.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">The Mistake: Posting "Pretty" Food Content</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The most common restaurant TikTok strategy looks like this: hire someone to come in with good lighting, film your signature dishes looking beautiful, add trending audio, post it. This is an Instagram strategy being applied to a TikTok algorithm — and TikTok doesn't care about beautiful.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          TikTok's algorithm distributes content based on engagement signals: watch time, rewatches, shares, saves, and comments. Aesthetically pleasing food content rarely drives any of those signals. Someone watches for 3 seconds, doesn't feel compelled to do anything, and scrolls. The algorithm reads that as low-quality content and stops distributing it.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">What Actually Works: The Reveal Hook</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The highest-performing restaurant content format on TikTok is what the food content world calls the "reveal." The structure is simple: the first frame creates a question or anticipation in the viewer's mind, and the rest of the video delivers the payoff. This compels rewatch — people watch again to see the transformation — and drives the "did you see this" share behavior that exponentially grows reach.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          For food content, reveals come in several forms:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 0 0 24px 24px; color: #2a2a2a; font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82;">
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>The plating reveal.</strong> Start with raw, unplated ingredients. Show the transformation into a finished dish. The contrast is inherently compelling and generates saves ("I want to try this").</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>The portion reveal.</strong> Walk in with what looks like a normal container or plate, then open it to show an absurd quantity. The "holy sh*t" moment is what gets shared — and Toronto food culture has a strong appetite for portion content.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>The price reveal.</strong> Build up the table with food — multiple dishes, drinks, the full spread — then reveal the price at the end. If it's genuinely good value, this is one of the most shared content formats in the GTA food scene.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>The cheese pull / steam release / sauce pour.</strong> Tactile, sensory moments that look almost uncomfortably satisfying on screen. If your cuisine has a natural version of this (melted cheese, a soup with visible steam, a sauce being ladled tableside), lean into it hard.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">The First 2 Seconds Are the Entire Video</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          On TikTok, the watch time metric starts at the instant someone doesn't immediately scroll away. Your first frame and the first 2 seconds of audio determine whether someone gives your video a chance. Most restaurant videos start with a slow pan or a shot of the exterior. That's already lost.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Start in the action. If it's a reveal, start at the peak moment of the process. If you're showing a dish being prepared, start at the most visually interesting part. If there's dialogue, the most compelling line should be in the first sentence. The viewer has already decided to keep watching or scroll before the 2-second mark — don't waste it on establishing shots.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Neighbourhood Content Outperforms Generic Content in the GTA</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Toronto's food community is intensely local. A video that opens with "best halal spot in Brampton" immediately signals to everyone in that community that this is for them. The algorithm distributes content to viewers based on location signals — and neighbourhood-specific content builds a loyal local audience faster than content aimed at "Toronto" generally.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Reference your intersection. Name the landmark nearby. Mention the community events in your area. This specificity doesn't limit your reach — the algorithm finds your neighbourhood's people across all of Toronto and the GTA. And those are exactly the customers who can actually walk through your door.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Consistency Over Virality</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Every restaurant we work with initially wants to go viral. Virality is real — we've had individual videos hit 5 million views — but it's not a strategy. What's actually sustainable is building an account that reliably reaches 10,000–50,000 people per video who are in your neighbourhood and interested in your cuisine type.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          That comes from posting consistently (4–5 times per week), iterating on what performs, and building a catalogue of content that the algorithm shows to new followers over time. The accounts that get 113K followers didn't do it on one viral video. They did it by posting good, relevant content consistently over 18 months — and letting the compound interest of the algorithm work.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Comments Are Revenue</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          When someone comments "omg I'm going this weekend" or "where is this?" on your video, that's not just engagement — that's a customer announcing their purchase intent to their own followers. Responding to every comment (especially from food creators with real audiences) and asking questions that invite responses in your caption generates the comment activity that tells the algorithm your content is worth distributing further.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The restaurants winning on TikTok in Toronto treat comment management as seriously as they treat their food. They respond within an hour. They create inside jokes with repeat commenters. They acknowledge when someone says they visited. That community building is what makes a TikTok following translate into actual loyal customers — not just passive viewers.
        </p>

        <div style="background: #f5f5f0; border-left: 3px solid #E85D04; padding: 24px; border-radius: 4px; margin: 40px 0;">
